{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506465"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:43:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:43:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2537"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2537"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.06,0.48,0.03,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2537"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106251"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2537"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2537"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88719"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5369"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44585"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106251"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has no current symptoms or concerns. His medical history includes well-controlled hypertension. He has no other significant medical history. His medications are irbesartan 150 mg daily. He does not take any other regular medications. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory and abdominal examination are unremarkable. He is an ex-smoker with a 30 pack-year history, having quit 8 years ago. He exercises regularly, playing tennis and walking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is interested to know if there is any evidence-based investigation he can undergo as a screening test for lung cancer. He is willing to pay for it himself if required.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate recommendation for lung cancer screening in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Thin-slice CT lung","Low dose CT chest","Sputum cytology","High resolution CT chest"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELung cancer accounts for almost 20% of all cancer deaths in Australia and has a low 5-year survival rate. The earlier lung cancer is detected, the better the outcome for an individual. Australia has announced the National Lung Cancer Screening Program (NLCSP) which will begin in mid-2025. The program will offer free \u003Cstrong\u003Elow dose CT scanning (LDCT)\u003C/strong\u003E screening to eligible people aged 50-70 years who have a smoking history of 30 pack-years or more and are either current smokers or have quit within the past 10 years. The program will involve a risk assessment and LDCT scan every two years for eligible participants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient described in this scenario fits the criteria for the upcoming Australian program based on his age and smoking history, and would be considered high-risk for lung cancer. If he were to undergo screening, LDCT would be the best modality. Additionally, factors such as current smoking status, understanding of screening outcomes, and fitness for potential surgery need to be assessed before undertaking screening. Limitations of LDCT screening include false-positive results, over-diagnosis, unnecessary treatment, and radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResearch has shown that \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not effective in screening for early lung cancers. \u003Cstrong\u003EThin-slice CT lung\u003C/strong\u003E involves very large radiation doses. \u003Cstrong\u003ESputum cytology\u003C/strong\u003E has lower sensitivity and specificity than LDCT, especially in detecting early-stage lung cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-resolution CT chest\u003C/strong\u003E takes high-resolution images of certain slices while skipping intervening spaces, potentially missing small lung nodules or early-stage tumors between slices. LDCT is superior for increasing early detection and improving patient outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The only recommended screening for lung cancer is a one to two yearly low dose CT chest scan.","Australia\u0027s National Lung Cancer Screening Program (NLCSP) is planned to begin in mid-2025.","Screening for lung cancer in the new Australian National Lung Cancer Screening Program (NLCSP) will include people aged 50-70, who have \u226530 pack year history and are current smokers or have quit in the last 10 years."],"references":["American Cancer Society: Lung Cancer Screening Guidelines [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.cancer.org/health-care-professionals/american-cancer-society-prevention-early-detection-guidelines/lung-cancer-screening-guidelines.html.","Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. National Lung Cancer Screening Program information for healthcare providers [Internet]. 2024. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/our-work/nlcsp/for-healthcare-providers","Division of Cancer Prevention, Centres for Disease Control and Prevention: Who should be screened for lung cancer? [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.cdc.gov/cancer/lung/basic_info/screening.htm#:~:text=may%20work%20better.-,The%20only%20recommended%20screening%20test%20for%20lung%20cancer%20is%20low,minutes%20and%20is%20not%20painful.","National Lung Screening Trial Research Team. Reduced lung-cancer mortality with low-dose computed tomographic screening. New England Journal of Medicine. 2011 Aug 4;365(5):395-409."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88719"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2537"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88719"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T09:54:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T09:54:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2537"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106251"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relation